lues.With chapters by distinguished critics from both sides of the Atlantic, the book ranges widely over contemporary poetry in America and the British Isles and explores transatlantic connections. Informed by current theoretical debates around ideas of value, the chapters focus these through clear discussion of texts in various media, including the work of a wide variety of poets and movements. The book carries forward the debate on the value of contemporary poetry amongst critics, scholars and practitioners while offering rich material for students and teachers of contemporary poetry and culture.Contributors: Jonathan Allison, Vicki Bertram, Paul Breslin, Cairns Craig, Robert Crawford, Lilias Fraser, Alan Golding, Romana Huk, Marjorie Perloff, Andrew Michael Roberts.Key FeaturesFocuses on the relationship between poetry and cultural practicesInformed by current theoretical debates about valueWide range of British and American poetry discussed by leading critics from both sides of the Atlantic  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aAllison, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAllison, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertram, Vicki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreslin, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Cairns, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawford, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraser, Lilias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolding, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuk, Romana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c